body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Consider the following code:

```verilog
module mcve1(i_value, o_value);
	input	wire	[3:0]	i_value;
	output	reg	[7:0]	o_value;

	integer k;
	always @(*)
	begin
		for(k=0; k<4; k=k+1)
			o_value[k] = i_value[k];
		o_value[4] = i_value[k];
		o_value[5] = i_value[k];
		o_value[6] = i_value[k];
		o_value[7] = i_value[k];
	end
endmodule
```

and process it with
```
yosys -p 'read -sv mcve1.v; synth; write_verilog mcve1y.v'
```

## Expected behavior

I'd expect the resulting Verilog code to look something like,

```verilog
    assign o_value = { {(5){i_value[3]}}, i_value[2:0] };
```

## Actual behavior

Instead, I get

```verilog
    assign o_value = { 4'hx, i_value };
```

The difference between the two is whether or not the loop variable maintains its last value after exiting the context of the for loop.

